## Migration: `EventProcessor` → .NET 8

### Problems in the original code

| API | Issue on .NET 8 |
|-----|-----------------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` (SYSLIB0006) |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | Obsolete (SYSLIB0046 in .NET 9), unreliable for `WaitOne` wakeup |
| `ManualResetEvent.WaitOne()` | Not cancellation-aware — can't be woken cooperatively |

### Pattern classification

- **`RunLoop`** → Cancellable work loop + Blocking call interruption
- **`Stop()`** → Uses both `Interrupt` and `Abort` to terminate the thread

### Migrated code

```csharp
using System.Threading.Channels;

public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly Channel<string> _channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Task? _workerTask;

    public void Start()
    {
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => RunLoopAsync(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task RunLoopAsync(CancellationToken token)
    {
        await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(token))
        {
            Handle(item);
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        _channel.Writer.TryWrite(item);
    }

    public async Task StopAsync()
    {
        _channel.Writer.Complete();   // signals no more items
        _cts.Cancel();                // wakes any pending read
        if (_workerTask is not null)
            await _workerTask.WaitAsync(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _cts.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* your logic */ }
}
```

### Why `Channel<T>` instead of manual lock + queue + event

| Concern | Old code | New code |
|---------|----------|----------|
| Thread-safe queue | Manual `lock` + `Queue<T>` | Built into `Channel<T>` |
| Signaling | `ManualResetEvent` (race-prone) | Channel blocks/resumes automatically |
| Cancellation | `Abort`/`Interrupt` | `CancellationToken` wakes `ReadAllAsync` |
| Lost items | Reset before dequeue = possible miss | Channel handles backpressure correctly |

### Key pitfalls to avoid

1. **Race condition in original code** — `WaitOne()` → `Reset()` → `Dequeue()` can lose signals if two `Enqueue` calls happen before `Reset`. `Channel<T>` eliminates this entirely.

2. **Don't forget `Channel.Writer.Complete()`** — without it, `ReadAllAsync` never finishes even after cancellation is requested (it would throw `OperationCanceledException` instead of exiting gracefully).

3. **Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** — leaking it causes timer/callback leaks.

4. **If you must keep the synchronous `Thread` style**, use `WaitHandle.WaitAny` instead:

```csharp
// Synchronous alternative (if async isn't viable)
private void RunLoop()
{
    var handles = new[] { _newEvent, _cts.Token.WaitHandle };
    while (!_cts.Token.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        WaitHandle.WaitAny(handles); // wakes on signal OR cancellation
        if (_cts.Token.IsCancellationRequested) break;

        _newEvent.Reset();
        lock (_lock) { if (_queue.Count > 0) Handle(_queue.Dequeue()); }
    }
}
```

5. **`Handle()` must also cooperate** — if `Handle` does long-running work, pass the token into it and check `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at checkpoints. Cooperative cancellation only works if the entire call chain participates.
